The paper focuses on realizing locomotion behaviors in a custom four-legged robot using deep reinforcement learning and kinematic motion primitives. This falls under the category of robotics (cs.RO) as the main objective is to develop an effective tool for quadrupedal walking. The use of deep reinforcement learning also suggests a focus on artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and machine learning (cs.LG). The paper also mentions the use of principal component analysis for analysis, which falls under the category of systems and control (cs.SY). Finally, the paper involves the reconstruction of joint trajectories, which could potentially involve computer vision techniques (cs.CV).
